## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

Your code is a **timeout enforcement** pattern with a **ThreadAbortException-as-control-flow** catch. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it simply doesn't work.

### APIs to Remove

| Removed API | Replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must check the token for cancellation to be responsive.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates for cleaner call stacks
            throw ex.InnerExceptions[0];
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Async overload — preferred when callers are already async.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Caller Migration

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework)
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ComputeExpensiveResult(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — work must accept and honor the token
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    token =>
    {
        // Check the token at regular intervals inside your work
        for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
        {
            token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
            // ... do a chunk of work ...
        }
        return finalResult;
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

---

### Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why It Matters |
|---|---|
| **Not passing `CancellationToken` into the work delegate** | Cancellation is now *cooperative*. If the work never checks the token, it runs to completion regardless of timeout — the old "forcibly kill the thread" behavior is gone. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` with a timeout allocates a `Timer` internally. Leaking it causes timer and callback leaks. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish your timeout from an external cancellation the caller may have requested. |
| **Expecting `Thread.Sleep` or blocking I/O to respond to the token** | `Thread.Sleep` ignores the token. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or use async I/O overloads that accept a `CancellationToken`. |
| **Truly uncooperative code (can't modify the work)** | If you cannot inject a `CancellationToken` (e.g., third-party library), move the work to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` on timeout. There is no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort` in modern .NET. |

### Key Paradigm Shift

> **Old model:** The runtime forcibly injects a `ThreadAbortException` at any point — the work code doesn't need to know about cancellation.
>
> **New model:** The work code must **voluntarily** check `CancellationToken` and throw `OperationCanceledException`. If it doesn't check, cancellation never happens. Design checkpoint frequency based on your acceptable timeout latency.
